text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Additional example of discriminating against regional accents%0a:Author: abbyl%0a:Original: [[Articles.AccentDiscriminationInEducation|AccentDiscriminationInEducation]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Simon_Y|Simon_Y]]%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 01.05.2021 - 15:32%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-192744-19010#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:27-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-192744-19010#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI found another example of discrimination in the UK against people speaking in regional accents in this reddit thread: https://www.reddit.com/r/AmItheAsshole/comments/iqsh5j/aita_for_telling_my_son_to_drop_his_fake/%0a%0aIn the thread, a parent complains that his young son started taking in a Yorkshire accent after moving to Yorkshire from Hampshire. The parent provides a few examples of his son's accent, saying that his son pronounces "right" as [ɹeɪt], "now" as [naɹ], and drops the [h] in words that contain the [h] sound. The parent concludes by saying he thinks the Yorkshire accent makes people unintelligent and that people with Yorkshire accents aren't taken seriously. As seen in the thread's comments, most people responded by saying that the parent was being extremely classist and snobby for his prescriptivism, which I completely agree with.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
